üìò Project Setup Guide

This README provides step-by-step instructions to configure the environment, set up the Oracle database, and create required users and tables.

üõ† Prerequisites

Make sure the following are installed on your system:

Node.js

Oracle SQL

SQL Plus

üöÄ Step-by-Step Setup
‚úÖ STEP 1: Install Node.js

Download and install Node.js from:
https://nodejs.org

Verify installation:

node -v
npm -v

‚úÖ STEP 2: Install Oracle SQL

Install Oracle Database and ensure it is running properly.

‚úÖ STEP 3: Open SQL Plus

Launch SQL Plus and login as a privileged user (like SYSTEM).

üë§ Create Database User
CREATE USER testuser IDENTIFIED BY test123;
GRANT CONNECT, RESOURCE TO testuser;

üîê Connect to the User
CONNECT testuser/test123@localhost:1521/FREEPDB1;

üóÑÔ∏è Create Tables
CREATE TABLE USERS (
    ID NUMBER GENERATED BY DEFAULT AS IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY,
    USERNAME VARCHAR2(50) UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    PASSWORD VARCHAR2(255) NOT NULL,
    ROLE VARCHAR2(50) NOT NULL
);

üë• Insert Default Users
INSERT INTO USERS (USERNAME, PASSWORD, ROLE)
VALUES ('operator', STANDARD_HASH('operator','SHA256'), 'operator');

INSERT INTO USERS (USERNAME, PASSWORD, ROLE)
VALUES ('hod-cse', STANDARD_HASH('hod-cse','SHA256'), 'hod-cse');

INSERT INTO USERS (USERNAME, PASSWORD, ROLE)
VALUES ('hod-ece', STANDARD_HASH('hod-ece','SHA256'), 'hod-ece');

INSERT INTO USERS (USERNAME, PASSWORD, ROLE)
VALUES ('hod-eee', STANDARD_HASH('hod-eee','SHA256'), 'hod-eee');

INSERT INTO USERS (USERNAME, PASSWORD, ROLE)
VALUES ('hod-mech', STANDARD_HASH('hod-mech','SHA256'), 'hod-mech');

INSERT INTO USERS (USERNAME, PASSWORD, ROLE)
VALUES ('hod-civil', STANDARD_HASH('hod-civil','SHA256'), 'hod-civil');

‚öôÔ∏è Backend Configuration
‚úÖ STEP 4: Create .env File

Inside the backend folder, create a file named .env and add your credentials:

üìå Notes

Ensure Oracle Database service is running before starting the backend.

Do not expose your .env file in public repositories.

Use .gitignore to exclude sensitive files.

‚úÖ Setup Complete!

Your environment is now ready. Start your backend server and connect it to the database successfully.
